	Process safety information regarding the hazards of ammonia, and operating and technical specifications for the refrigeration systems and the associated equipment;
	Written procedures for operating and maintaining the refrigeration system;
	Training for personnel involved with system operations and maintenance;
	Written procedures for safely introducing modifications to the process;
	Investigating releases of ammonia and near miss incidents and implementing measures to prevent recurrence; 
	Written procedures for conducting hot work on or near the process;
	Contractor management policies to ensure contract employee safety while on facility premises;
	Audit procedures for ensuring that the programs are being implemented in accordance with the regulations; and
	Employee involvement in program development and implementation.

In addition, engineering controls have been implemented to reduce the chance of an accidental release to the environment.  These are comprised of equipment monitoring systems and safety cutouts to shut off the equipment when operating parameters exceed safe operating limits.  Relief valves on pressurized ammonia vessels prevent equipment rupture in the event of overpressurization.  Annual inspections and tests are performed by an outside refrigeration contractor to ensure these controls are in good working order. 

Five Year Accident History
A review of the facilitys five year accident history showed that there have been no incidents at the facility that meet the RMP criteria for a reportable accident (onsite deaths, injuries, or significant property damage; or known offsite deaths, injuries, property damage, environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place).  In addition, there have been no incidents at the facility in the last five years that resulted in a release of more than the Federal Reportable Quantity (100 pounds).

